# Fixture IRI-006: empty base path — merge-paths algorithm
#
# RFC 3986 §5.2.3 "Merge Paths" rule: if the base URI has a defined
# authority and an EMPTY path, the merged path is `"/" + reference_path`.
# This prevents path references from being concatenated directly onto the
# authority component.
#
# Example: base = `http://example` (no trailing slash → empty path).
#           reference = `foo`.
#           Correct result: `http://example/foo`.
#           Wrong result:   `http://examplefoo`  (string concatenation).
#
# Hypothesis: A simple resolver that does string concatenation of
# authority + path reference when the base path is empty will produce
# `http://examplefoo` — an IRI that looks like a different authority.
# The Merge Paths algorithm in RFC 3986 §5.2.3 inserts the `/` but this
# step is non-obvious and frequently omitted in hand-rolled resolvers.
#
# Spec: RFC 3986 §5.2.3 (Merge Paths)
#       RFC 3986 §5.2.2 (Reference Resolution — step for empty base path)

@base <http://example> .
@prefix p: <http://example.org/pred/> .

# Must resolve to http://example/foo  (slash inserted by merge algorithm)
<foo>      p:name "relative-against-no-trailing-slash" .

# Must resolve to http://example/bar/baz
<bar/baz>  p:name "relative-path-against-empty-base-path" .

# Must resolve to http://example/  (empty reference path + authority → root)
<>         p:name "empty-reference-empty-base-path" .
